did.abstract:
This collection contains material amassed by Jerome T. Barrett pertaining to his career as a labor mediator and commissioner and director of the Office of Technical Services of the Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service. There are also materials related to the United States Consilitation Service (USCS) founded in the Department of Labor in 1913.
The material dates between 1913-2013.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This collection contains material amassed by Jerome T. Barrett pertaining to his career as a labor mediator and director of the Office of Technical Services of the Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service. The material dates between 1913-2013. Included are oral history interviews, articles, handbooks, and annual reports. Please note that this collection is only partially processed.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Jerome T. Barrett was born in 1932 in St. Paul, Minnesota. He received his Bachelors degree from the College of St. Thomas (1959) and his Masters degree from the University of Minnesota (1963). His Doctorate of Education is from The George Washington University (1984). Barrett worked as a field examiner for the National Labor Relations Board from 1961 to 1963. Following that he worked for one year as a mediator at the Minnesota Office of Labor Conciliator. He served as a mediator for the Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service in District of Columbia and Milwaukee from 1964 to 1969. He was assistant director of Alternative Dispute Resolution and Mediation at the National Center for Dispute Resolution, 1969 to 1970. Barrett returned to government service in 1970 as chief of the Division of Public Employee Relations at the U.S. Department of Labor. He rejoined the Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service in 1973 as director of the Office of Technical Services. He taught labor relations at Northern Kentucky University from 1982 to 1985 and was an industrial relations specialist for the Department of Labor's Bureau of Labor-Management Cooperative Programs until his retirement in 1990. He is the author of over 200 published articles and papers. He is co-author of Interest Based Bargaining: A User Guide (2005) and P.A.S.T. Is the Future: A Model for Interest-Based Collective Bargaining(1998) and author of A History of Alternative Dispute Resolution (2004). He is a member of numerous mediation and arbitration-related professional associations. He passed away on November 5, 2020.

did.unittitle: The Friends of Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service History Archive

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service was established as an independent government agency in 1947. Its mission is to prevent or minimize the impact of labor-management disputes by providing mediation, conciliation and voluntary arbitration. Its predecessor organization, the U. S. Conciliation Service, was established in 1918 within the Department of Labor.

The Friends of FMCS History was founded by Dr. Jerome T. Barrett in 1992. Its purpose was to gather, preserve and publicize the history of the Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service and its predecessor, the U.S. Conciliation Service. Dr. Barrett began collecting materials relating to FMCS and USCS history in the spring of 1964. Former commissioners and other FMCS staff would hand over their own history-related materials as they retired and Dr. Barrett would save materials as they were being readied for disposal. He conducted interviews with mediators as part of his doctoral dissertation and these became part of the Friends Archive. The Friends Archive was transferred to the Special Collections Research Center in 2011 and 2012.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This subseries is arranged according to its original order. Roughly chronological, the subseries starts with materials from the FMCS's first Director, Cyrus Ching, and goes through to John Calhoun Wells.
Note: The order of materials restarts with Box 78 Folder 9, as these materials were added after initial processing. They follow the same arrangement pattern.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains materials produced by or directly related to FMCS Directors (and Acting Directors) from 1942-2010. Included are materials from Cyrus Ching, James Greenwood, Whitely McCoy, Joseph Finnegan, William Simkin, J. Curtis Counts, William Usery, Jr., James Scearce, Wayne Horvitz, Kenneth Moffett, Kay McMurray, Bernard DeLury, Brian Flores, John Calhoun Wells, Richard Barnes, Peter Hurtgen, Scot Beckenbaugh, and George Cohen.

The materials in this subseries vary widely. Included are internal memoranda, correspondence, reports, press releases and news clippings, as well as articles and speeches by FMCS Directors and Commissioners. This subseries' "General" folders also contain a variety of miscellaneous materials.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains typed transcripts and cassette recordings of 192 oral history interviews conducted by Jerome Barrett on behalf of the Friends of the Federal Mediation and Concilation Service History between the years of 1983 and 2012. Among those interviewed are numerous former FMCS directors, including founding director Cyrus Ching. Interview topics include biographical information, the organization and operation of the FMCS, and personal accounts of important labor disputes, including the U.S. Postal Strike of 1970. Seventeen interviews were conducted by Martha Ross and fifteen were conducted by othjer interviewers.

arrangement.p: This subseries is arranged alphabetically by the name of the person being interviewed. Multiple interviews of the same person are arranged chronologically, and when both a transcript and sound recording of the same interview are included the transcript is listed first.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains speeches by FMCS Commisioners and other in the labor mediation industry dating from 1952-1985. Many of the speeches were given at FMCS conferences or as part of FMCS workshops. Topics include women in labor mediation disputes, the changing role of mediation, and FMCS organizational development.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains articles and essays pertaining to the FMCS and the field of labor dispute mediation, dating from 1948-2007. Nearly all of the materials are published articles, but also included are unpublished essays and book excerpts. A few of the articles and essays were written by former FMCS Directors, including Kenneth Moffet and John Calhoun Wells, but most were written by FMCS mediators and other employees.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries is comprised of biographical sketches of USCS conciliators, compiled from 1946-1951, and of FMCS mediators, compiled from 1960-1982. Included for each conciliator/mediator is a photograph, basic biographical information, education information, and employment experience prior to and with the USCS/FMCS. In addition, many include additions noting retired or deceased individuals.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This subseries is arranged into two parts. The first, in Boxes 13 and 14, contains two complete, bound copies of the FMCS Commissioners Handbook. The second, in Boxes 15 and 16, contains a third copy of the FMCS Commissioners Handbook, arranged in its original order.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains three copies of the FMCS Commissioners Handbook. The first belonged to Commissioner Robert T. Castrey and the second to the FMCS Pittsburgh Field Office. The third copy is not specifically labelled. While all three copies contain essentially the same materials, each is slightly different. A "Record of Revisions" in each copies reveals that each copy was edited independently and at different times between 1955 and 1972.

The FMCS Commissioners Handbook contains a wide variety of information on the organization. Included is information on the FMCS' policies, procedures, budget, personnel and services. Also included are numerous forms used in the operation of the FMCS.
